To end in the terminal t9, any sentence generated by the grammar must use the only start‐production that can place t9 at the very end:

 S → NT5 NT24 with NT24 → 't9'

(Neither of the other two start rules can yield t9 as the last symbol, and every multicharacter expansion of NT24 finishes with t5, t8 or t0, never with t9.)

Hence the rest of the string (all but the final t9) must be produced by NT5.

NT5, however, can expand only as

 NT5 → NT6 NT5   (left-recursive)  
 NT5 → NT23 NT14

Because the recursion is on the left, the rightmost symbols generated by any NT5 are those produced by the non-recursive alternative NT23 NT14, with their ultimate last symbol coming from NT14.

Now examine NT14’s possibilities:

 NT14 → 't5'   |   't8'  
 NT14 → NT22 NT14 (prefixes something in front of another NT14)  
 NT14 → NT12 NT2   (prefixes two symbols in front of another)

Whatever sequence NT14 produces, its final token is necessarily either t5 or t8 – never t0.

Therefore every string derived from NT5 must end in t5 or t8, yet the portion of the target string that NT5 would have to generate ends in t0 (the penultimate symbol of the whole string). This contradiction means no derivation is possible.

Consequently, the grammar cannot generate the given 24-token string.

No

The start symbol S can expand in three different ways:

1. S → NT5 NT24  (NT24 can give only one terminal when it is used directly)
2. S → NT33 NT7  (NT7 produces a single terminal, never t8, so this branch cannot end with “… t8”)
3. S → NT23 NT31

Because the given word ends with the pair “… t8 t8”, possibility 2 is impossible (NT7 can only be t0, t2, t3 or t7).  
Possibility 1 would force NT24 to be the last symbol of the word and hence to yield exactly one terminal.  The very last terminal of the string is t8, making NT24 = t8, and NT5 would then have to generate the first 26 tokens.  NT5, however, can only start with either a token produced by NT23 (t8, t1, t7) or by NT6 (its first token can never be t6).  Since our word begins with t6, this branch is impossible too.

Therefore we must use

  S ⇒ NT23 NT31.

NT31 may produce only one terminal by the rule NT31 → 't8', matching the last symbol of the string.  
Thus NT23 has to generate exactly the first 26 symbols

t6 t0 t0 t3 t8 t1 t0 t3 t4 t0 t8 t4 t3 t0 t8 t8 t1 t5 t9 t0 t3 t3 t3 t1 t4 t8.

NT23 has the rule NT23 → NT6 NT6.  
A first NT6 can generate the prefix

t6 t0 t0 t3 t8 t1 t0 t3 t4 t0 t8 t4 t3 t0

like this:

NT6  
⇒ NT24 NT18  
⇒ (NT9 NT33) NT18  
⇒ (‘t6’  NT33)  ‘t0’  
⇒ ‘t6’ t0 t0 t3 t8 t1 t0 t3 t4 t0 t8 t4 t3 t0.

A second NT6 can then generate

t8 t8 t1 t5 t9 t0 t3 t3 t3 t1 t4 t8

using the recursive rule NT6 → NT15 NT6 (NT15 supplies the initial t8, NT6 is reused for the rest, eventually terminating with its direct terminal productions and NT20 → t8).

Thus the whole first 26-token segment is in L(NT23); appending the final t8 supplied by NT31 gives the entire 27-token string in L(S).

Consequently the grammar does generate the given string.

Yes
